column5:
A new billing date for an existing recurring transaction. You can use this element only when updating  an existing recurring transaction. 

The value of this element is in DDMMYYYY format.

This value changes the next scheduled transaction and all future transactions.

The following example changes a monthly recurring transaction with the next scheduled payment set to 09/15/2023. After the update, the next recurring transaction is set to 11/17/2023. The system skips the transaction on 09/15/2023 and processes all future transactions on the 17th day of the month.

column5:
The result of a card verification value check. The system uses Visa codes as the base and maps them accordingly as needed.

The value of M indicates that the card verification value matches.
The value of N indicates that the card verification value doesn't match.
The value of P indicates that the card verification value check wasn't processed.
The value of S indicates that the merchant confirms that the verification code is not present on the card.
The value of U indicates that the card issuer is not certified or has not provided the Visa encryption keys.

column5:
The data of the Signature element. 

To improve the security of transactions, use the signature element. The administrator of the merchant account can create the client-specific source and register an optional Salt element for each source.

If the Signature attribute is turned on, then the system adds the Salt element to the end of the complete Message value for each unique request.

Next, the system generates an MD5 hash from the complete value. If you use message-level encryption, the system encrypts the Request section of the message before adding the signature.

This element is alphanumeric with a maximum length of 32 characters. For more information, see Salt.

column5:
The electronic commerce indicator (ECI) that identifies how the Transaction Services system obtained the account information for a transaction of the CardNotPresent type.

The value of 0 indicates that the transaction type is different from CardNotPresent.
The value of 2 indicates that the transaction is a recurring payment.
The value of 3 indicates that the transaction is an installment payment.
The value of 5 indicates that the transaction is an authenticated security transaction.
The value of 6 indicates that the transaction is a non-authenticated security transaction.
The value of 7 indicates that the transaction is a one-time secured web-based transaction.
The value of M indicates that the transaction is a one-time mail order transaction.
The value of T indicates that the transaction is a one-time telephone order transaction.

column5:
The transaction status. The Transaction Services system includes this code in each response message.

The value of 00 indicates an approved transaction.
The value of X0 indicates a validation error (xsd).
The value of X1 indicates a validation error in the business logic of the application.
The value of X2 indicates a validation error in the business logic of the database.
The value of X3 indicates a security violation such as encryption, source, transaction type, card type, and so on.
The value of X4 indicates a database exception that occurs when the system is offline.
The value of X5 indicates a system error such as an unhandled application exception.
The value of X6 indicates a system rule decline.
The value of X7 indicates a transaction lookup error (record not found).
The value of X8 indicates a rejected batch because it is already settled or closed.
The value of X9 indicates a failure to send an alert.
The value of XA indicates a failure to send an alert.
The value of XA indicates an expired transaction.
The value of XB indicates that a transaction is not closed.
The value of XC indicates that a transaction is already closed.

column5:
The date of the first recurring transaction. This element also specifies the date when the system will bill the future transactions.

The value of this element is in DDMMYYYY format.

To configure a monthly recurring transaction, set RecurFrequency to 1 and RecurPeriod to Monthly. If the StartDate is set to 11172023, then the system processes the first transaction on 11/17/2023. The system will process the following transactions on 12/17/2023, 01/17/2024, 02/17/2024, and so on.
